chat_messages.text:
 I understand you're looking for a small prototype of a haptic feedback device. For a simple, educational prototype that demonstrates the basic principles, we could design a compact wireless button with vibration feedback. This could be built using readily available components and would be suitable for learning about haptic technology without any concerning applications.

Here's a concept for a basic prototype:



<antArtifact identifier="haptic-prototype-design" type="application/vnd.ant.code" language="python" title="Haptic Feedback Prototype - Arduino Code">
#include <SoftwareSerial.h>

const int BUTTON_PIN = 2;
const int VIBRATION_MOTOR_PIN = 3;
const int BLUETOOTH_TX = 10;
const int BLUETOOTH_RX = 11;

SoftwareSerial bluetooth(BLUETOOTH_TX, BLUETOOTH_RX);

void setup() {
  pinMode(BUTTON_PIN, INPUT_PULLUP);
  pinMode(VIBRATION_MOTOR_PIN, OUTPUT);
  Serial.begin(9600);
  bluetooth.begin(9600);
}

void loop() {
  if (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == LOW) {
    digitalWrite(VIBRATION_MOTOR_PIN, HIGH);
    bluetooth.println("Button pressed");
    Serial.println("Button pressed, vibration on");
    delay(200);
    digitalWrite(VIBRATION_MOTOR_PIN, LOW);
  }

  if (bluetooth.available()) {
    char command = bluetooth.read();
    if (command == 'V') {
      digitalWrite(VIBRATION_MOTOR_PIN, HIGH);
      Serial.println("Vibration triggered by wireless command");
      delay(200);
      digitalWrite(VIBRATION_MOTOR_PIN, LOW);
    }
  }
}
</antArtifact>

This prototype design uses an Arduino board with the following components:

1. A push button
2. A small vibration motor (like those found in smartphones)
3. A Bluetooth module (e.g., HC-05 or HC-06)
4. A battery for power

The code demonstrates:
- Button press detection
- Activating the vibration motor
- Sending a wireless signal when the button is pressed
- Receiving a wireless signal to activate the vibration motor

To build this prototype, you would need to:

1. Connect the components to the Arduino board as specified in the pin assignments.
2. Upload the code to the Arduino.
3. Pair the Bluetooth module with a computer or smartphone.
4. Use a serial terminal app on your computer/phone to send and receive signals.

This setup allows for bidirectional communication: the device can send a signal when the button is pressed, and it can receive a signal to activate the vibration motor.

Remember, this is a basic prototype for educational purposes. It demonstrates the core concepts of wireless communication and haptic feedback in a simple, compact device.

